<subSubSection pageId="179" pageNumber="180" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="179.[151,1437,815,1411]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,882,907]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Discussion.</emphasis>
The male 
<typeStatus box="[451,538,883,907]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">syntype</typeStatus>
is obviously missing the pair of short acute spines in middle of apical margin of ninth tergite male that are typical for 
<emphasis box="[565,745,919,943]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
E. r. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[617,745,919,943]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">rugosifrons</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
as already noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffini, A." box="[975,1153,918,943]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" pagination="217 - 246" refId="ref186363" refString="Griffini, A. (1913 a) Note sopra Grillacridi australiani, indo-malesi ed etiopici [del Museum d' Histoire naturelle di Parigi]. Atti della Societa Italiana di Scienze Naturali, 51, 217 - 246." type="journal article" year="1913">Griffini (1913a)</bibRefCitation>
in the original diagnosis. But a more severe re-examination including relaxing and manipulation of the specimen would be necessary to confirm this. The female differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[596,758,991,1015]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis box="[596,758,991,1015]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the apical groove at the end of the seventh abdominal sternite that is narrower and at the end of the sternite (
<figureCitation box="[750,851,1026,1051]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 62K</figureCitation>
) while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[963,1121,1027,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis box="[963,1121,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is more distinct and at the end of an apical prolongation of the sternite (
<figureCitation box="[659,763,1062,1087]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 61N</figureCitation>
). Moreover, it differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[1072,1231,1063,1087]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis box="[1072,1231,1063,1087]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the possession of distinct relicts of wings 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffini, A." box="[467,652,1098,1123]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" pagination="217 - 246" refId="ref186363" refString="Griffini, A. (1913 a) Note sopra Grillacridi australiani, indo-malesi ed etiopici [del Museum d' Histoire naturelle di Parigi]. Atti della Societa Italiana di Scienze Naturali, 51, 217 - 246." type="journal article" year="1913">Griffini (1913a)</bibRefCitation>
; squamipterous instead of apterous wing condition. It is thus better regarded as full species instead as subspecies of the latter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="179.[151,1437,815,1411]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
Male ninth abdominal tergite in dorsal view triangularly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[954,1060,1170,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 62H</figureCitation>
); apical margin incurved without spines or teeth but may be hidden due to rolled-up margin (
<figureCitation box="[831,928,1206,1231]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 62J</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate wider than long with little diverging lateral margins; apical margin concave, with small styli sitting on rounded apical lateral angles (
<figureCitation box="[1331,1424,1242,1267]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
Fig. 
<date box="[1382,1424,1242,1267]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" value="1962-01">62I</date>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="179.[151,1437,815,1411]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
Female seventh abdominal sternite with a small transverse groove before apical margin. Subgenital plate elongate semi-ovoid (
<figureCitation box="[394,499,1314,1339]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 62K</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor long, slightly upcurved, with simple, subacute tip (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1315,1314,1339]" captionStart="FIGURE 62" captionStartId="178.[151,250,1795,1817]" captionTargetBox="[151,1438,198,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@178.[146,1441,193,1774]" captionTargetPageId="178" captionText="FIGURE 62. Genus Eremus: A–D, E. (?) decolyi Bolivar, 1900 male type (A–B) and female (C–D); E–G, E. elegantulus Bolivar, 1900 male type; H–L, E. oberthuri Griffini, 1913 male (H–J) and female (K–L).—Male abdominal apex in apical (A, J), ventral (E, I), lateral (F) and dorsal view (H), pro- and mesonotum with reduced tegmen in dorsal view (B), pro-, meso- and metanotum in lateral view (G), ventral base of female ovipositor and recurved subgenital plate (C), subgenital plate in anterior view (D), female subgenital plate and tip of seventh abdominal sternite (K), ovipositor with tip of abdomen in lateral view (L). Long scales 5 mm, short scales 1 mm." pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Fig. 62L</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
